{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505152","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505152"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:26:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:26:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2411"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2411","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2411"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.1,0.05,0.59,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2411"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50203"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2411","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2411"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2411"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35474"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1315"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11114"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1736"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1805"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3571"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35111"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43144"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44672"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50203","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50203"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the GP clinic requesting contraception. She is sexually active with her long-term male partner and uses condoms intermittently. She mentions that, during sexual intercourse with her partner, on one occasion the condom broke and she was worried that this might happen again. Her home urine pregnancy test was negative on two separate readings. She is keen on starting on contraception and wants advice on this.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has no plans to become intentionally pregnant in the next 3 \u2013 5 years but may choose to do so in the future. She wishes to avoid visiting the GP clinic regularly for contraception or renewal of any contraceptive medication. She does not have any unexplained vaginal bleeding or discharge. Her history is unremarkable. She is a non-smoker and drinks occasionally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer physical examination is unremarkable, and her vital signs are all within the normal range. The patient decides that she wants to try a copper intrauterine device.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important mechanism of action for this contraceptive method?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thickening of the cervical mucus","Obstruction of the fallopian tubes","Decreased follicular stimulating hormones (FSH) and luteinising hormones (LH)","Induction of endometrial inflammation","Inhibition gonadotrophin-releasing hormone (GnRH) and luteinising hormones (LH)"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EContraception should always be offered for sexually-active women who do not wish to be pregnant. Contraception, such as an intrauterine device, is best used in this patient as there is past evidence of inconsistencies and inefficacy of barrier contraception i.e. condoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECopper intrauterine devices (IUD) probably have several mechanisms of action. First of all, the presence of the IUD itself in the uterine cavity stimulates a local \u003Cstrong\u003Eendometrial inflammatory \u003C/strong\u003Ereaction that appears to interfere with the mobility of sperm and prevents them from reaching the fallopian tubes. The copper that is released from these IUDs is thought to have a direct detrimental effect on sperm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther (plastic-based) IUDs such as the Mirena have several mechanisms of action, including thickening of cervical mucus which impairs the ability of sperm to travel upwards through the cervix. Other hormonal contraceptive methods containing progestin may also thicken the cervical mucus to inhibit sperm ascension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EObstructing the fallopian tubes are achieved by performing surgical ligation of the fallopian tubes. This blocks the passage of ova to uterine cavity and prevents sperm and ovum meeting. This procedure is irreversible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe intramuscular depot injection, medroxyprogesterone acetate, is a hormonal contraception that works by decreasing FSH and LH levels, thereby inhibiting ovulation. This method requires a 3 monthly intramuscular depot by a medical professional.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInhibition of GnRH and LH is achieved by progestin-containing oral contraceptives. This causes the suppression of ovulation, inhibits endometrial proliferation and thickens the cervical mucus.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intrauterine devices provide effective contraception and are relatively free of side effects."],"references":["Jatlaoui TC, Riley HEM, Curtis KM. The safety of intrauterine devices among young women: a systematic review. Contraception 2017; 95:17.","Hubacher D. Copper intrauterine device use by nulliparous women: Review of side effects. Contraception 2007; 75:S8."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35474"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2411"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35474","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRe